<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,536]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,462,223,248]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" reason="1">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The habitus of this species (
<figureCitation box="[786,853,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1728,1751]" captionTargetBox="[263,1347,203,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-88@12.[240,1348,195,1707]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Epimetopus holotypes, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum." pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) is very similar to that of several other members of the 
<emphasis box="[194,292,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Costatus</emphasis>
group; reliable determinations will be based on examination of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1193,1278,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–15" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1641,1664]" captionTargetBox="[175,1414,226,1578]" captionTargetId="figure-73@14.[151,1436,195,1619]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 12–15. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). The median lobe is nearly parallel-sided in dorsal view and quite blunt apically; in lateral aspect it is strongly curved. The aedeagus is similar in general shape to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[681,860,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis box="[681,860,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">E. ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[877,961,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–23" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1672,1695]" captionTargetBox="[256,1332,191,1643]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[227,1360,167,1679]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 20–23. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), but differs in shapes of the median lobe and parameres, and curvature of the medial lobe. Externally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Oliva" authorityYear="1986" box="[841,952,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hintoni">
<emphasis box="[841,952,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">E. hintoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly larger than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[1208,1387,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis box="[1208,1387,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">E. ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(ca. 1.71 vs. 
<quantity box="[246,350,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.56" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" unit="mm" value="1.56">1.56 mm</quantity>
), but otherwise they are very similar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,536]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,439,464]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
